    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A cold front forms when a dense, chilly air mass slides underneath a lighter, warmer air mass, forcing the warm air to rise rapidly. As this warm air ascends, it cools and condenses, often creating clouds and precipitation before the cold air pushes the warm air out of the way. When a cold front moves through an area, the air pressure typically drops sharply as the leading edge approaches, then rises steadily once the cold air has fully replaced the warm air behind it. This pressure drop is a key indicator that the front is near, signaling a potential shift in weather patterns.\n\nIn short, the high pressure of the cold air mass overrides the low pressure of the warm air mass, causing a noticeable drop in barometric readings as the front arrives. This process is a classic example of how different air masses interact to create dynamic weather systems.",
